sy, Roma and Traveller communities in the context of global crises. Contributors assess the impact of the pandemic on their engaged research, evaluating novel methods and technologies. They reveal how current research practice blurs the borders between activism and scholarship, and they argue the need for innovative collaborations with local communities. Showcasing emerging aspects of GRT-related scholarship, this book makes a key contribution to larger debates on the positionality of researchers and the politics of research, and affirms the continued value of rigorous ethnography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh1 aCavaliero, Tamsin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChirițoiu, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFotta, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFotta, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFriel, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGay y Blasco, Paloma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGay y Blasco, Paloma, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGómez Ávila, Demetrio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeoco, Luxa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManrique, Nathalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontañés Jiménez, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiemontese, Stefano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarafian, Iliana, ec